at patch.<br /><br />If this was the cause of the problem (and it looks likely), wouldn't<br />it be nicer to instead make sure that __restore_processor_state() is<br />made to use only low-level code and easy to verify?<br /><br />That function is already marked "notrace" because it is so fragile,<br />and it does the segment register reloads manually with inline asms.<br /><br />Could we make it use "native_load_gs_index()" instead? Or even go all<br />the way and make it do that user-space %gs load internally with inline<br />asm, the way it already does the kernel space %gs?<br /><br />(Maybe "native_wrmsrl()" too?)<br /><br />Or is this actually all supposed to work even under PV? That sounds really iffy.<br /><br />               Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
